Its restrictions and the environment it's fostered, is slowing processes down and isolating us. But all the Aus mental health sites have specific details for Covid, and I'll share a few things I've found (or some stalwarts I often fall back on).  Here we go:

If you have not had symptoms/signs of mental ill-health before, it can be hard to guage how bad it is. One good place to start is a mental health (k10) checklist. You can complete one online. Take a deep breath and give it a go:  https://t.co/PWR4VjBzXd

Lifeline and Beyond Blue both have some lists of practitioner recommendations -- but go with someone you're comfortable with, someone close, and if you're comfortable, ask mates for recs: https://t.co/BeDLvA4mXC

make yourself safe during suicide risk, one excellent way to do this is using Beyond Blue's Suicide Safety Plan app, Beyond Now. I have one, and my partner and parents can see my plan, so they know what I need when I feel suicidal. https://t.co/KUYfaBZBrF

One post-script (of many? we'll see what else I remember!): being a carer of a mentally ill person is v hard and complex. My partner gives a lot of himself to me to keep me safe and alive every day. I am encouraging him to find his own support system too: https://t.co/jZaCxO3pIb

Lifeline now runs a text service w their crisis support team, which my mate described as 'literally like texting with a friend'. The number is: 0477 13 11 14. It's a great, accessible alternative if you (understandably) do not want to/cannot call). https://t.co/u0Ir5MKdQy
